text:
A small data.frame



df1 <- data.frame(name = c("George", "Stan", "Carly"),
                  age  = c(75,15,31),
                  retired = c(T,F,F))

title: Lecture 05

Subsetting

There are 3 subsetting operators:

[ –> vectors
[[ –> lists

$ –> data.frames

Subsetting can be combined with assignment.

🔮 Looking forward 🔮

Raster objects objects are built on multi-dimensional arrays, where each layer corresponds to a separate array slice.
Like base R matrices, raster objects store values in a column-major order, meaning data is arranged column-wise in memory, optimizing performance for certain matrix operations.

title: Lecture 07
text: Data Visualization

title: Lecture 07
text:
ggplot

ggplot2 is a library is based on the grammar of graphics
the idea is you can build every graph from the same few components:

a data set
geom(s)
a coordinate system

ggplot2 provides a programmatic interface for specifying

what variables to plot
how they are displayed
general visual properties.




library(ggplot2)

title: Lecture 07
text:
ggplot

Therefore, we only need minimal changes if the underlying data changes or if we decide to change our visual.
This helps create publication quality plots with minimal amounts of adjustments and tweaking.
ggplot likes data in the ‘long’ format: i.e., a column for every dimension, and a row for every observation. (more on this next week…)

title: Lecture 07
text:
Components of a ggplot:

ggplot graphics are built step by step by adding new elements and layers

Data
Geometry (geom)
Aesthetic mapping
Theme

Elements of a plot are layered by iteratively adding elements
These can be added in a series of 5 steps:

Setup
Layers
Labels
Facets
Themes

title: Lecture 07
text:
Example Data for today …

library(gapminder); library(dplyr);library(ggplot2)

(gm2007 = filter(gapminder, year == 2007))
#> # A tibble: 142 × 6
#>    country     continent  year lifeExp       pop gdpPercap
#>    <fct>       <fct>     <int>   <dbl>     <int>     <dbl>

title: Lecture 07
text:
1. The Setup: canvas


An empty canvas can be initialized with ggplot()


ggplot()

title: Lecture 07
text:
1. The Setup: data


Every ggplot requires a data argument (data.frame/tibble)


ggplot(data = gm2007)

title: Lecture 07
text:
1. The Setup: Aesthetic Mappings



Aesthetic mappings describe how variables in the data are visualized
Denoted by the aes argument
Can be set in ggplot() and/or in individual layers.
Aesthetic mappings in the ggplot() call, can be seen by all geom layers.
The X and Y axis of the plot as well colors, sizes, shapes, fills are all aesthetic.
If you want to have an aesthetic fixed (that is not vary based on a variable) you need to specify it outside the aes()



ggplot(data = gm2007, 
       aes(x = gdpPercap, y = lifeExp))

title: Lecture 07
text:
2. Layers

The + sign is used to add layers to a ggplot setup
Layers can define geometries, compute summary statistics, define what scales to use, or even change styles.
In general a plot construction will look like this:


DATA  |>  
  ggplot(aes(x, y)) + 
  LAYER 1 + 
  LAYER 2 + 
  …

title: Lecture 07
text:
2. Layers: Geometry

Many layers in ggplot2 are called ‘geoms’.
geoms are the geometric objects (points, lines, bars, etc.) that can be placed on a graph to visualize the X-Y mapping of the input data/aes
They are called using functions that start with geom_*.
Examples include:

points (geom_point, for scatter plots, dot plots, etc)
lines (geom_line, for time series, trend lines, etc)
boxplots (geom_boxplot)
… and many more!



ls(pattern = '^geom_', env = as.environment('package:ggplot2'))
#>  [1] "geom_abline"            "geom_area"              "geom_bar"              
#>  [4] "geom_bin_2d"            "geom_bin2d"             "geom_blank"            
#>  [7] "geom_boxplot"           "geom_col"               "geom_contour"          
#> [10] "geom_contour_filled"    "geom_count"             "geom_crossbar"         
#> [13] "geom_curve"             "geom_density"           "geom_density_2d"       
#> [16] "geom_density_2d_filled" "geom_density2d"         "geom_density2d_filled" 
#> [19] "geom_dotplot"           "geom_errorbar"          "geom_errorbarh"        
#> [22] "geom_freqpoly"          "geom_function"          "geom_hex"              
#> [25] "geom_histogram"         "geom_hline"             "geom_jitter"           
#> [28] "geom_label"             "geom_line"              "geom_linerange"        
#> [31] "geom_map"               "geom_path"              "geom_point"            
#> [34] "geom_pointrange"        "geom_polygon"           "geom_qq"               
#> [37] "geom_qq_line"           "geom_quantile"          "geom_raster"           
#> [40] "geom_rect"              "geom_ribbon"            "geom_rug"              
#> [43] "geom_segment"           "geom_sf"                "geom_sf_label"         
#> [46] "geom_sf_text"           "geom_smooth"            "geom_spoke"            
#> [49] "geom_step"              "geom_text"              "geom_tile"             
#> [52] "geom_violin"            "geom_vline"

title: Lecture 07
text:
2. Layers: Geometry

A plot must have at least one geom, but there is no maximum.
Adding geoms to a ggplot follows the pattern:


ggplot(data = <DATA>, aes(X, Y)) + 
  <GEOM_FUNCTION>(mapping = aes(<MAPPINGS>))
  <GEOM_FUNCTION>(mapping = aes(<MAPPINGS>))


Note again that the aesthetics placed in the ggplot call are the global parameters for the plot, and the aesthetics placed in each geom are specific to that geom.

title: Lecture 07
text:
A first geom_* …



ggplot(data = gm2007,
       aes(x = gdpPercap, y = lifeExp))

title: Lecture 07
text:
A first geom_* …



ggplot(data = gm2007,
       aes(x = gdpPercap, y = lifeExp)) +
  geom_point()

title: Lecture 07
text:
2. Layers: Geometry


Like the set up, geoms can be modified with aesthetics (aes). Examples include:

position (i.e., on the x and y axes)
color (“outside” color)
fill (“inside” color)
shape
line type
size

. . .
Each geom accepts only a subset of these aesthetics
(refer to the geom help pages (e.g. ?geom_point) to see what mappings each geom accepts.

text:
2. Layers: data.frame driven/fixed?



ggplot(data = gm2007, aes(x = gdpPercap, y = lifeExp)) + 
  geom_point(col = "red")










ggplot(data = gm2007, aes(x = gdpPercap, y = lifeExp)) + 
  geom_point(aes(col = continent))

title: Lecture 07
text:
3. Labels

Now that you have drawn the main parts of the graph. You might want to add labs that clarify what is being shown.
This can be done using the labs layer.
The most typical are: title, x, and y but other options exist!

title: Lecture 07
text:
4. Facets

In the previous chart, we showed a scatterplot for all countries plotted in the same chart. What if you want one chart for each continent?
Such separation is called faceting
facet_wrap() takes in a formula as the argument.
Formulas look like this RHS ~ LHS (where RHS = right hand side, LHS = left hand side)


The item on the RHS corresponds to the column. The item on the LHS defines the rows.

In facet_wrap, the scales of the X and Y axis are fixed to accommodate all points by default.
This makes the comparison of values more meaningful because they would be in the same scale.
The scales can be made free by setting the argument scales=free.

title: Lecture 07
text:
Grids vs Wrap

facet_wrap(): Used for one faceting variable (or two), automatically wraps facets into rows and columns for a flexible layout.
facet_grid(): Used for two faceting variables, arranges plots in a strict row-column grid.


Layout Difference: facet_wrap() optimizes space, while facet_grid() maintains a fixed structure.
Use Case: Use facet_wrap() for many categories without hierarchy; use facet_grid() for structured relationships between two variables.

title: Lecture 07
text:
5. Theme

Great! Now we just need to polish our plots…
ggplot offers a themeing system:

elements specify the non-data elements that you can control. For example,


plot.title controls the appearance of the plot title;
axis.ticks.x controls the ticks on the x axis;
legend.key.height, controls the height of the keys in the legend.


Each element is associated with an element function, which describes the visual properties. For example,


element_text() sets the font size, color and face of text elements like plot.title.


The theme() function which allows you to override default elements:


For example theme(plot.title = element_text(color = "red")).

title: Lecture 07
text:
Built in themes
Wow! That’s a lot :) Fortunately, ggplot comes with many default themes that set all of the theme elements to values designed to work together harmoniously.

title: Lecture 09
text:
Data structure vs Data format

data.frames are a list with atomic vecotrs of the same length.
data.frames (and list and vector) are data structures
The format of the data.frame however can be widely variable….

title: Lecture 09
section: Data Format – the quest for “tidy data”
text:
Data Format – the quest for “tidy data”

These are all representations of the same underlying data, but they are not equally easy to use. One dataset, the tidy dataset, will be much easier to work with inside the tidyverse.
Tidy data demands three interrelated rules
Each variable must have its own column.
Each observation must have its own row.
Each value must have its own cell.



It’s impossible to only satisfy \(2/3\) so … a simpler guideline:

Put each dataset in a tibble.
Put each variable in a column.

title: Lecture 09
text:
The world is messy …

For most real problems, you’ll need to do some cleaning/tidying
Once you understand what data you have, you typically have to resolve one of two common issues:

One variable might be spread across multiple columns.
One observation might be scattered across multiple rows.

To fix these, we look at the tidyr package (within the tidyverse)

title: Lecture 09
text:
Longer

A common issues is a dataset where some of the column names are not names, but rather values we want:


# A tibble: 2 × 3
  country `1952` `2007`
  <fct>    <dbl>  <dbl>
1 Brazil    50.9   72.4
2 India     37.4   64.7

title: Lecture 09
text:
Longer (and narrower)

To make the column names an attribute of the dataset, we need to pivot the data
This pivot will effectively make the data longer and narrower…
To do this we look to tidyr::pivot_longer()

title: Lecture 09
text:
Longer



lifeExp_tab
# A tibble: 2 × 3
  country `1952` `2007`
  <fct>    <dbl>  <dbl>
1 Brazil    50.9   72.4
2 India     37.4   64.7



lifeExp_tab |> 
  pivot_longer(cols = c(`1952`, `2007`), 
               names_to = "year", 
               values_to = "lifeExp")
# A tibble: 4 × 3
  country year  lifeExp
  <fct>   <chr>   <dbl>
1 Brazil  1952     50.9
2 Brazil  2007     72.4
3 India   1952     37.4
4 India   2007     64.7

title: Lecture 09
text:
Putting it together …

long4a = lifeExp_tab |> 
  pivot_longer(c(`1952`, `2007`), names_to = "year", values_to = "lifeExp")

long4b = gdpPercap_tab |> 
  pivot_longer(c(`1952`, `2007`), names_to = "year", values_to = "gdpPercap")

left_join(long4a, long4b)
# A tibble: 4 × 4
  country year  lifeExp gdpPercap
  <fct>   <chr>   <dbl>     <dbl>
1 Brazil  1952     50.9     2109.
2 Brazil  2007     72.4     9066.
3 India   1952     37.4      547.
4 India   2007     64.7     2452.

title: Lecture 09
text:
Wider (and shorter)

pivot_wider() is the opposite of pivot_longer().
We use it to solve the opposite problem… when an observation is scattered across multiple rows.


table2
# A tibble: 8 × 4
  country  year type       value
  <fct>   <int> <chr>      <dbl>
1 Brazil   1952 lifeExp     50.9
2 Brazil   1952 gdpPercap 2109. 
3 Brazil   2007 lifeExp     72.4
4 Brazil   2007 gdpPercap 9066. 
5 India    1952 lifeExp     37.4
6 India    1952 gdpPercap  547. 
7 India    2007 lifeExp     64.7
8 India    2007 gdpPercap 2452.

title: Lecture 09
text:
Wider (and shorter)

To allow an attribute to define a variable name, we need to pivot the data
This pivot will effectively make the data wider and shorter
To do this we look to tidyr::pivot_wider()

title: Lecture 09
text:
When wide is right!

All dplyr data manipulation works on columns and rows
So when we are filtering, selecting, mutating, grouping, and summarizing wide data is best

title: Lecture 09
text:
When long is right!

Yesterday we noted that ggplot prefers data to be long.
This is because when applying aesthetics or facets we want the variable to be an attribute of the dataset

title: Lecture 09
text:
Internal groupings

nest() and map() are functions from the tidyverse, primarily used with the tidyr and purrr packages.
They allow for efficient list-column workflows and functional programming in R.
Useful for grouped operations, iterative calculations, and data wrangling.

title: Lecture 09
text:
What is nest()?

nest() converts a grouped dataset into a list-column format.
It allows you to keep related observations together in nested data.frames.


data <- data.frame(
  group = rep(c("A", "B"), each = 3),
  x = c(1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6),
  y = c(2, 4, 6, 8, 10, 12)
)

data
  group x  y
1     A 1  2
2     A 2  4
3     A 3  6
4     B 4  8
5     B 5 10
6     B 6 12

nested_data <- data |> 
  nest(data = -group)

nested_data
# A tibble: 2 × 2
  group data            
  <chr> <list>          
1 A     <tibble [3 × 2]>
2 B     <tibble [3 × 2]>

nested_data$data[[1]]
# A tibble: 3 × 2
      x     y
  <dbl> <dbl>
1     1     2
2     2     4
3     3     6

nested_data$data[[1]]$x
[1] 1 2 3

nested_data$group[[1]]
[1] "A"

Explanation: - The data tibble contains two groups (A and B) with corresponding x values. - nest(data = -group) creates a new tibble where each group has a nested data frame containing the x values.

title: Lecture 09
Lecture 09
text:
Combining nest() and map()

nest() structures the data into groups.
map() applies functions to each nested dataset.
Can be used for modeling, summaries, and transformations.

Example: Linear Regression by Group

(nested_data <- nest(gm2007, -continent))
# A tibble: 5 × 2
  continent data             
  <fct>     <list>           
1 Asia      <tibble [33 × 5]>
2 Europe    <tibble [30 × 5]>
3 Africa    <tibble [52 × 5]>
4 Americas  <tibble [25 × 5]>
5 Oceania   <tibble [2 × 5]> 

model_results <- nested_data |> 
  mutate(model = map(data, ~lm(lifeExp ~ gdpPercap, data = .x)))

model_results$continent[1]
[1] Asia
Levels: Africa Americas Asia Europe Oceania

title: Lecture 09
text:
What is broom?

The broom package helps tidy up model outputs for further analysis or reporting.
It converts model objects (like from lm()) into tidy data frames that are easy to manipulate.

Key functions from broom include:
tidy() for converting model coefficients and statistics into a data frame. glance() for providing a one-row summary of a model’s performance. augment() for adding model diagnostics (e.g., residuals, fitted values) to the original data.

title: Lecture 09
text:
Extracting Model Summaries

model_example = nested_data |> 
  mutate(model   = map(data, ~lm(lifeExp ~ gdpPercap, data = .x)),
         summary = map(model, broom::tidy)) 

nested_data |> 
  mutate(model   = map(data, ~lm(lifeExp ~ gdpPercap, data = .x)),
         summary = map(model, broom::glance)) |> 
  unnest(summary)
# A tibble: 5 × 15
  continent data     model  r.squared adj.r.squared  sigma statistic   p.value
  <fct>     <list>   <list>     <dbl>         <dbl>  <dbl>     <dbl>     <dbl>
1 Asia      <tibble> <lm>       0.475         0.458   5.86     28.1    9.13e-6
2 Europe    <tibble> <lm>       0.722         0.713   1.60     72.9    2.80e-9
3 Africa    <tibble> <lm>       0.148         0.131   8.98      8.69   4.86e-3
4 Americas  <tibble> <lm>       0.349         0.321   3.66     12.3    1.87e-3
5 Oceania   <tibble> <lm>       1           NaN     NaN       NaN    NaN      
# ℹ 7 more variables: df <dbl>, logLik <dbl>, AIC <dbl>, BIC <dbl>,
#   deviance <dbl>, df.residual <int>, nobs <int>

model_example |> 
  unnest(summary) 
# A tibble: 10 × 8
   continent data     model  term        estimate std.error statistic    p.value
   <fct>     <list>   <list> <chr>          <dbl>     <dbl>     <dbl>      <dbl>
 1 Asia      <tibble> <lm>   (Intercept)  6.59e+1   1.37e+0     48.1    1.07e-30
 2 Asia      <tibble> <lm>   gdpPercap    3.88e-4   7.32e-5      5.30   9.13e- 6
 3 Europe    <tibble> <lm>   (Intercept)  7.23e+1   6.94e-1    104.     8.50e-38
 4 Europe    <tibble> <lm>   gdpPercap    2.15e-4   2.51e-5      8.54   2.80e- 9
 5 Africa    <tibble> <lm>   (Intercept)  5.16e+1   1.64e+0     31.4    1.38e-34
 6 Africa    <tibble> <lm>   gdpPercap    1.02e-3   3.47e-4      2.95   4.86e- 3
 7 Americas  <tibble> <lm>   (Intercept)  7.06e+1   1.12e+0     63.1    2.77e-27
 8 Americas  <tibble> <lm>   gdpPercap    2.70e-4   7.69e-5      3.51   1.87e- 3
 9 Oceania   <tibble> <lm>   (Intercept)  7.74e+1 NaN          NaN    NaN       
10 Oceania   <tibble> <lm>   gdpPercap    1.11e-4 NaN          NaN    NaN       

Explanation: - The tidy() function extracts the coefficients from the linear models stored in the model column and formats them into a tidy data frame. - This makes it easier to summarize or report on the results.

x = nested_data|> 
  mutate(model = map(data, ~ lm(lifeExp ~ gdpPercap, data = .x))) |> 
  mutate(lm = map(model, broom::tidy),
         summary   = map(model, summary),
         r2 = map_dbl(summary, "r.squared")) |> 
  unnest(lm) |> 
  select(-data, -model)


y = select(x, continent, term, estimate) 

pivot_wider(y, names_from = continent, values_from = estimate) |> 
  janitor::clean_names()

       y = "Linear Model Intercept")

  geom_col() +
  facet_wrap(~term, scales = "free_y") +

title: Lecture 09
text:
Conclusion
nest() is useful for grouping and restructuring data. map() enables functional programming and efficient iteration. broomprovides a way to tidy up model outputs for easier interpretation and reporting.
Together, they provide a powerful framework for handling grouped analyses in R.

title: Lecture 09
text:
Many identically structured data.frames
Binding rows

bind_rows() and bind_cols() are functions from the dplyr package.
They are used to combine data frames by rows or columns.

title: Lecture 09
text:
bind_rows()

Used to stack data frames on top of each other.
Useful when datasets have the same column names and types.


df1 <- data.frame(id = 1:3, value = c("A", "B", "C"))
df2 <- data.frame(id = 4:6, value = c("D", "E", "F"))

combined_rows <- bind_rows(df1, df2)

glimpse(combined_rows)
Rows: 6
Columns: 2
$ id    <int> 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6
$ value <chr> "A", "B", "C", "D", "E", "F"

title: Lecture 09
text:
bind_cols()

Used to combine data frames side by side.
Requires the data frames to have the same number of rows.


df3 <- data.frame(score = c(10, 20, 30))
df4 <- data.frame(rank = c("First", "Second", "Third"))

combined_cols <- bind_cols(df3, df4)

glimpse(combined_cols)
Rows: 3
Columns: 2
$ score <dbl> 10, 20, 30
$ rank  <chr> "First", "Second", "Third"

title: Lecture 09
text:
Summary
lm() is a powerful function for linear regression in R.
summary() provides key insights.
Diagnostic plots help validate assumptions.
Predictions can be made for new data with predict()

Data structure vs Data format

data.frames are a list with atomic vectors of the same length.
data.frames (and list and vector) are data structures
The format of the data.frame however can be widely variable….

title: Lecture 08
text:
Longer

A common issue is a dataset where some of the columns are not names, but rather values we want:



country19522007Brazil50.91772.390India37.37364.698

title: Lecture 08
text:
Longer (and narrower)

In long format, each observation is recorded in a single row, with a column for the variable and another for the value.
To make the column names an variable, we need to pivot the data making the data longer and narrower…
To do this we look to tidyr::pivot_longer()

Wider (and shorter)

pivot_wider() is the opposite of pivot_longer().
We use it to solve the opposite problem… when an observation is scattered across multiple rows.

title: Lecture 08

Wider (and shorter)

To allow an variable to become a set of columns, we need to pivot the data making the data wider and shorter
To do this we use tidyr::pivot_wider()

title: Lecture 08
text:
When wide is right!

All dplyr data manipulation works on columns and rows
So when we are filtering, selecting, mutating, grouping, and summarizing wide data is best

title: Lecture 08
text:
When long is right!

Yesterday we noted that ggplot prefers data to be long.
This is because when applying aesthetics or facets we want the variable to be an attribute of the dataset

title: Lecture 08
text:
For example …


Wide

table_wide |> 
  ggplot(aes(x = year, y = gdpPercap)) +
  geom_line(aes(color = country)) + 
  facet_wrap(~country) + 
  theme_bw() + 
  theme(legend.position = "none")









Long

table_long |> 
  ggplot(aes(x = year, y = value)) +
  geom_line(aes(color = country)) + 
  facet_grid(type~country, scales = "free_y") + 
  theme_bw() + 
  theme(legend.position = "none")

title: Lecture 08
section: Data Format – the quest for “tidy data”
text:
Data Format – the quest for “tidy data”
These are all representations of the same underlying data, but they are not equally easy to use. One dataset, the tidy dataset, will be much easier to work with inside the tidyverse.


Tidy data demands three interrelated rules


Each variable must have its own column.
Each observation must have its own row.
Each value must have its own cell.












It’s impossible to only satisfy \(2/3\) so … an simpler guideline:

Put each dataset in a tibble.
Put each variable in a column.

title: Lecture 08
text:
The world is messy …


For most real problems, you’ll need to do some cleaning/tidying …



Once you understand what data you have, you typically have to resolve one of two common issues:

One variable might be spread across multiple columns.
One observation might be scattered across multiple rows.





To fix these, we look at the tidyr package (within the tidyverse)


library(tidyr)

"tidyr" %in% tidyverse_packages()
[1] TRUE

title: Lecture 08
text:
Summary
When to Use Long Data?

Easier for aggregation, analysis, and plotting.

Works well with ggplot2 and other tidyverse tools.

Facilitates handling of missing values.

Preferred for repeated measures or time series data.


When to Use Wide Data?

Simpler for certain analyses (e.g., regression models).

Easier to read when dealing with few variables.

Can be easier for sharing datasets with non-technical audiences.

title: Lecture 08
text:
BUT … the world is messy …


For most real problems, you’ll need to do some cleaning/tidying …



Once you understand what data you have, you typically have to resolve one of two common issues:

One variable might be spread across multiple columns.
One observation might be scattered across multiple rows.





To fix these, we look at the tidyr package (within the tidyverse)


library(tidyr)

"tidyr" %in% tidyverse_packages()
[1] TRUE

title: Lecture 08
text:
Example

Remember the idea of “binding”? Where a set of values are “bound” to a name?

You job: - Always consider what - for your analysis - is a name and what is data

Often your needs don’t match the way data was collected/curated by others!
Your needs can range dramatically within a workflow as well

What needs to be manipulated?
How do you establish keys?
What is needed for visualization?
…

title: Lecture 08
text:
Example


Wide

# All country/Year/GDP combinations are unique rows
table_wide
# A tibble: 4 × 4
  country  year lifeExp gdpPercap
  <fct>   <int>   <dbl>     <dbl>
1 Brazil   1952    50.9     2109.
2 Brazil   2007    72.4     9066.
3 India    1952    37.4      547.
4 India    2007    64.7     2452.

table_wide |> 
  ggplot(aes(x = year, y = gdpPercap)) +
  geom_line(aes(color = country)) + 
  facet_wrap(~country) + 
  theme_bw() + 
  theme(legend.position = "none")









Long

# All country/Year/LifeExp/GDP combinations are unique rows
table_long
# A tibble: 8 × 4
  country  year type       value
  <fct>   <int> <chr>      <dbl>
1 Brazil   1952 lifeExp     50.9
2 Brazil   1952 gdpPercap 2109. 
3 Brazil   2007 lifeExp     72.4
4 Brazil   2007 gdpPercap 9066. 
5 India    1952 lifeExp     37.4
6 India    1952 gdpPercap  547. 
7 India    2007 lifeExp     64.7
8 India    2007 gdpPercap 2452. 

table_long |> 
  ggplot(aes(x = year, y = value)) +
  geom_line(aes(color = country)) + 
  facet_grid(type~country, scales = "free_y") + 
  theme_bw() + 
  theme(legend.position = "none")

title: Lecture 08
text:
Assignment
Question 1: Make a faceted plot of the cumulative cases & deaths by USA region. Your x axis should be the date and the y axis value/count. To do this you will need to join and pivot the COVID-19 data.
We can break this task into 7 steps:



Read in the COVID-19 data

Create a new data.frame using the available state.abb, state.name, state.region objects in base R. Be intentional about creating a primary key to match to the COVID data!


df = data.frame(region = state.region,
                ...,
                ...)


Join your new data.frame to the raw COVID data. Think about right, inner, left, or full join…
split-apply the joined data to determine the daily, cumulative, cases and deaths for each region
Pivot your data from wide format to long
Plot your data in a compelling way (setup, layers, labels, facets, themes)
Save the image to your img directory with a good file name and extension!

title: Lecture 09
text:
Remember … Vectors

Vectors come in two types: atomic and lists
For atomic vectors, all elements must have the same type;
For lists, elements can have different types.
NULL serves as a generic zero length vector.
This diagram - taken from here - illustrates the basic relationships:




df$list_element = vector("list", length = nrow(df))

title: Lecture 09
text:
Today

Linear Models: Introduction to Models in R


Deep Dive on OLS in a few weels


Understanding the nest/map approach

title: Lecture 09
text:
The lm() Function in R
Basic Syntax:

model <- lm(y ~ x, data = dataset)

Where:

y: Dependent variable (response).
~: Describes a formula as LHS ~ RHS (remember facet_*)
x: Independent variable (predictor).
dataset: data.frame containing variables.

Example:

gm2007 <-  filter(gapminder, year == 2007)
lm_model <- lm(lifeExp ~ gdpPercap, data = gm2007)



lm_model

Call:
lm(formula = lifeExp ~ gdpPercap, data = gm2007)

Coefficients:
(Intercept)    gdpPercap  
  5.957e+01    6.371e-04

title: Lecture 09
text:
Multiple Linear Regression
Syntax for Multiple Predictors:

lm_model <- lm(y ~ x1 + x2 + x3, data = dataset)


Allows for multiple independent variables.

lm_model <- lm(lifeExp ~ gdpPercap + pop, data = gm2007)



Allows for interaction terms with *

lm_model <- lm(lifeExp ~ gdpPercap + pop + pop*gdpPercap, data = gm2007)

title: Lecture 09
text:
Viewing Model Summary
Use summary() to inspect results. Provides coefficients, R-squared, p-values, etc.

summary(lm_model)

Call:
lm(formula = lifeExp ~ gdpPercap + pop + pop * gdpPercap, data = gm2007)

Residuals:

-22.466  -5.910   1.877   6.942  13.393

gdpPercap      6.575e-04  6.393e-05  10.284   <2e-16 ***
pop            9.386e-09  6.428e-09   1.460    0.146    
gdpPercap:pop -4.595e-13  7.586e-13  -0.606    0.546    
---
Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

Residual standard error: 8.89 on 138 degrees of freedom
Multiple R-squared:  0.4693,    Adjusted R-squared:  0.4578 
F-statistic: 40.68 on 3 and 138 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16

title: Lecture 09
text:
Diagnostic Plots: Checking Assumptions



Residuals vs. Fitted: Check linearity.
Normal Q-Q: Check normality.
Scale-Location: Check homoscedasticity.
Residuals vs. Leverage: Detect influential points.



par(mfrow = c(2,2))
plot(lm_model)

text:
Making predictions using lm()
Make Predictions:

                       gdpPercap = mean(gdpPercap),
                       pop = mean(pop)))

      1 
66.9592

title: Lecture 09
text:
Across a population






Pipe Notes


Remember the difference in pipes described in lab 2?
Tidyverse Pipe (%>%)
From the magrittr package (and used in dplyr), %>% allows greater flexibility than |>, such as:

Using placeholders (.) when the first argument isn’t where the function expects input.
Automatically handling non-standard evaluation in dplyr.





(new_data <- summarise(gm2007,
                       gdpPercap = mean(gdpPercap),
                       pop = mean(pop)))
# A tibble: 1 × 2
  gdpPercap       pop
      <dbl>     <dbl>
1    11680. 44021220.

df = data.frame(country = 1:100) |> 
  mutate(gdpPercap = abs(rnorm(n(), mean(gm2007$gdpPercap), sd(gm2007$gdpPercap))),
         pop = abs(rnorm(n(), mean(gm2007$pop), sd(gm2007$pop)))) %>%
  mutate(lifeExp = predict(lm_model, .))

title: Lecture 09
section: Linear Models as the Basis for Machine Learning
text:
Linear Models as the Basis for Machine Learning
Why is lm() Fundamental to ML?
Linear regression is the simplest form of a predictive model.
Forms the basis of many ML algorithms, such as:

Logistic Regression (for classification)
Support Vector Machines (linear kernel)
Neural Networks (linear combinations in layers)
Generalized Linear Models (GLMs)
Regularization techniques like Ridge and Lasso regression extend lm() to prevent overfitting.

Many deep learning models rely on matrix multiplication, a fundamental concept in linear regression.

title: Lecture 09
text:
Challenge!
Starting with the gapminder dataset, compute a continent-by-contient regression of lifeExp ~ gdpPercap

gapminder |> 
  filter(year == 2007) |> 
  group_by(continent) %>% 
  mutate(lm = lm(lifeExp ~ gdpPercap, data = .))
Error in `mutate()`:
ℹ In argument: `lm = lm(lifeExp ~ gdpPercap, data = .)`.
ℹ In group 1: `continent = Africa`.
Caused by error:
! `lm` must be a vector, not a <lm> object.

title: Lecture 09
text:
Unnest

Much like ungroup removes a group structure, unnest removes a nest structure


unnest(nested_data, data)
# A tibble: 6 × 3
  group     x     y
  <chr> <dbl> <dbl>
1 A         1     2
2 A         2     4
3 A         3     6
4 B         4     8
5 B         5    10
6 B         6    12

title: Lecture 09
text:
Working over list-columns
Verbs like mutate work well across columns, but cannot work over nested lists (e.g. a list-column of a data.frame (list!))

For this, we need additional tooling.


library(purrr)

"purrr" %in% tidyverse_packages()
[1] TRUE

title: Lecture 09
Lecture 09
text:
So what?
So you might be asking why all this extra work over group_by/summarize?

(gm2007 <-  filter(gapminder, year == 2007) )

title: Lecture 09
text:
The lm() Function in R
Basic Syntax:

model <- lm(y ~ x, data = dataset)

Where:

y: Dependent variable (response).
~: Describes a formula as LHS ~ RHS (remember facet_*)
x: Independent variable (predictor).
dataset: data.frame/tibble containing variables.

Example:

data   <-  penguins |> 
  drop_na()


(model <- lm(flipper_length_mm ~ body_mass_g, data = data))

Call:
lm(formula = flipper_length_mm ~ body_mass_g, data = data)

Coefficients:
(Intercept)  body_mass_g  
   137.0396       0.0152

lm_model <- lm(y ~ x1 + x2 + x3, data = dataset)

title: Lecture 09
section: Linear Models as the Basis for Machine Learning
text:
Linear Models as the Basis for Machine Learning
Why is lm() Fundamental to ML?
Linear regression is the simplest form of a predictive model and forms the basis of many ML algorithms, such as:
1. Logistic Regression (for classification)

Example: Predicting water contamination based on pH, turbidity, and dissolved oxygen.

2. Support Vector Machines (Linear Kernel)

Example: Classifying land cover types (urban vs. vegetation) using remote sensing data.

3. Neural Networks (Linear Combinations in Layers)

Example: Modeling soil moisture dynamics with meteorological variables.

title: Lecture 09
text:
Summary

visualizing data structure
identifying missing values
checking correlations
inferring data types

lm() is a powerful function for linear regression in R.

Returns an s3 object of class lm

summary() provides key insights about lm models
predict() can be make predictions for new data
broom is a usefull library for tidying up model outputs

title: Lecture 09
text:
Internal groupings

nest() and map() are functions from the tidyverse, primarily used with the tidyr and purrr packages.
They allow for efficient list-column workflows and functional programming in R.
Useful for grouped operations, iterative calculations, and data wrangling.

title: Lecture 09
text:
What is nest()?

nest() converts a grouped dataset into a list-column format.
It allows you to keep related observations together in nested data.frames.


nested_data <- penguins |> 
  nest(data = -species)

title: Lecture 09
text:
Working over list-columns
Verbs like mutate work well across columns, but cannot work over nested lists (e.g. a list-column of a data.frame (list!))

For this, we need additional tooling.


library(purrr)
"purrr" %in% tidyverse_packages()
[1] TRUE

purrr
purrr is an R package that enhances functional programming by providing a consistent and powerful set of tools for working with lists and vectors. It is part of the tidyverse and helps simplify iteration, replacing traditional for loops and apply functions with more readable and efficient alternatives.
Key Features of purrr:

map() Functions – Apply a function to each element of a list or vector.

map() → Returns a list
map_lgl() → Returns a logical vector
map_int() → Returns an integer vector
map_dbl() → Returns a double (numeric) vector
map_chr() → Returns a character vector
map2(.x, .y, .f) → Iterates over two vectors.
pmap(list(...), .f) → Iterates over multiple vectors.

title: Lecture 09
Lecture 09
text:
So what?

So you might be asking why all this extra work over group_by/summarize?
The reason is the flexability that lists offer over vector in what they can store!


penguins |> 
  group_by(species) %>% 
  mutate(lm = lm(flipper_length_mm ~ body_mass_g, data = .))
Error in `mutate()`:
ℹ In argument: `lm = lm(flipper_length_mm ~ body_mass_g, data = .)`.
ℹ In group 1: `species = Adelie`.
Caused by error:
! `lm` must be a vector, not a <lm> object.

title: Lecture 09
text:
Combining nest() and map()

nest() structures the data into groups.
map() applies functions to each nested dataset.
Can be used for modeling, summaries, and transformations.

Example: Linear Regression by Group

(nested_data <- nest(penguins, -species))
# A tibble: 3 × 2

1 Adelie    <tibble [152 × 7]>
2 Gentoo    <tibble [124 × 7]>

  mutate(model = map(data, ~lm(flipper_length_mm ~ body_mass_g, data = .x)))

S3 is a lightweight and flexible object-oriented system in R that allows defining custom classes by assigning a “class” attribute to lists or other base R objects. Methods for S3 classes are dispatched based on the generic function called, using a naming convention like generic.classname(), and R selects the appropriate method based on the object’s class. While S3 lacks formal encapsulation and inheritance mechanisms, it is widely used in R packages due to its simplicity and ease of extension.

What is broom?

The broom package helps tidy up model outputs for further analysis or reporting.
It converts model objects (like from lm()) into tidy data frames that are easy to manipulate.

title: Lecture 09
text:
Conclusion
nest() is useful for grouping and restructuring data. map() enables functional programming and efficient iteration. broom() provides a way to tidy up model outputs for easier interpretation and reporting.
Together, they provide a powerful framework for handling grouped analyses in R.

title: Lecture 09

title: Lecture 09
text:
What is Modeling?

A model is a simplified representation of reality.
They helps understand/explain, predict, and analyze complex systems.
Common in environmental science, engineering, and many other fields.

title: Lecture 09
text:
Types of Models
Physical Models

Scale replicas of real-world systems.
Example: A wind tunnel model of an airplane.

Conceptual Models

Diagrams or frameworks illustrating relationships.
Example: The water cycle.

Mathematical Models

Use equations to describe processes.
Example: Hydrologic models for streamflow prediction.

Statistical Models

Use data and probability to make predictions.
Example: Regression models for climate trends.

title: Lecture 09
text:
Why Use Models?
Models …
✅ allow testing scenarios without real-world risks.
✅ provide insights into system behavior.
✅ provide interpretability and easier communication
✅ support improving understanding and making predictions.
✅ are usefull for decision-making and policy development.

Limitations of Models
🔴 Simplifications: Models are always approximations, not perfect representations if the critical driving forces arent captured, accuracy can be unpredicatable.
🔴 Uncertainty: Data quality and assumptions affect accuracy.
🔴 Computational Cost: Some models require high processing power.

title: Lecture 09
text:
Modeling in Environmental Science

Hydrologic models for water resource management.
Climate models to predict future conditions.
Ecosystem models for biodiversity studies.

title: Lecture 09
text:
Limitations of Models
🔴 Simplifications: Models are always approximations, not perfect representations if the critical driving forces arent captured, accuracy can be unpredicatable.
🔴 Uncertainty: Data quality and assumptions affect accuracy.
🔴 Computational Cost: Some models require high processing power.

title: Lecture 09
text:
Data Cleaning
What is data cleaning?

The process of detecting, correcting, or removing corrupt, inaccurate, or incomplete data.
Ensures data quality, reliability, and usability for analysis.

Why is data cleaning important?

Duplicates and missing data can significantly impact the performance and reliability of machine learning and statistical models. Here’s how each issue affects modeling:

title: Lecture 09
text:
Impact of Duplicates
Bias in Model Training:
🔴 If duplicates exist in the training data, the model may overfit to repeated observations, leading to an unrealistic representation of real-world data.
Skewed Distributions:
🔴 Duplicates can artificially inflate the frequency of certain patterns, misleading statistical analyses and causing models to favor duplicated values disproportionately.
Computational Inefficiency:
🔴 Extra, redundant data increases computational load, leading to longer training times and higher memory usage without adding new information.
Overestimation of Model Performance:
🔴 If duplicates exist in both training and test sets, the model might appear to perform better than it actually does because it has seen the exact data points before.

title: Lecture 09
text:
Impact of Missing Data
Bias in Predictions:
🔴 If missing values are not random (e.g., more missing values in a particular category), models trained on incomplete data may develop biased decision rules.
Reduced Model Accuracy:
🔴 Missing values reduce the amount of information available to learn patterns, leading to weaker predictions and generalizations.
Issues with Certain Algorithms:
🔴 Some models, like linear regression and decision trees, can handle missing data through imputation or by ignoring missing values, but others (like most neural networks) require complete data.
Complications in Feature Engineering:
🔴 Many feature transformations, such as standardization and encoding, may not work correctly with missing values, leading to poor feature representation.

title: Lecture 09
text:
Handling Duplicates and Missing Data
Options for Duplicates:

Remove exact duplicates when they don’t add information.
Analyze near-duplicates to determine if they should be merged, retained, or removed.


df <- df %>% 
  distinct()

For Missing Data:

Use imputation techniques (mean, median, mode, regression-based, or KNN imputation). -Remove records if missing data is minimal and its removal won’t introduce bias.
Use models that handle missing data natively (e.g., XGBoost can handle missing values).
Properly handling duplicates and missing data improves model performance, reliability, and interpretability, ensuring that predictions are more accurate and generalizable.


## Removal
df <- df %>% 
  drop_na()

# Imputation
df <- df %>% 
  mutate(x = mean(x, na.rm = TRUE))

title: Lecture 09
text:
Linear Models

A Linear Model is a statistical method for modeling relationships between a dependent variable and one or more independent variables.

✅ Commonly used in regression analysis.
✅ Simple and interpretable.
✅ Useful for prediction and understanding relationships in data.
✅ Forms the foundation for more complex models.

title: Lecture 09
text:
Introduction to Linear Models

Linear models help us understand relationships between variables.
Describe relationships between variables using a mathematical equation that assumes a linear relationship of “best fit”.
They take the form: \[ y = \beta_0 + \beta_1 x + \epsilon \]
Where:

( y ) is the response variable.
( x ) is the predictor variable.
\(\beta_0\) is the intercept (value of ( y ) when ( x = 0 )).
\(\beta_1\) is the slope (change in ( y ) for a unit change in ( x )).
\(\epsilon\) is the error term.

title: Lecture 09
section: Linear models are widely used for:
text:
Linear models are widely used for:

Prediction & Forecasting – Estimating future values based on historical data.
Understanding Relationships – Identifying and quantifying the impact of independent variables on a dependent variable.
Interpolation & Extrapolation – Making estimates within or beyond observed data ranges.
**Feature Selection & Data Reduction – Identifying key predictors in complex datasets.
Control & Optimization – Helping in decision-making and optimizing processes in fields like finance, engineering, and science.

Examples include simple linear regression (one predictor) and multiple linear regression (multiple predictors), commonly used in economics, engineering, and environmental science.

title: Lecture 09
section: How do we fine the “Line of Best Fit”?
text:
How do we fine the “Line of Best Fit”?
Method of Ordinary Least Squares (OLS)
Ordinary Least Squares finds the line of best fit for a linear model (in the form of y = mx + b) by minimizing the sum of the residuals squared

where:

residuals are the distance between the sample value (for the dependent variable) and the value predicted by the equation for each value of the independent variable.

title: Lecture 09
section: Four Main Assumptions for linear regression
text:
Four Main Assumptions for linear regression

Lineraity of the relationship between dependent and independent variables


Dot



Independence of the errors (no serail correlation): Error in one measurement (observation) should not influence errors for any other observations




Homoscedasticty (constant variance) of the errors

versus time
versus the predicted values





Normality of the residuals

title: Lecture 09
text:
Equation skill
How do we quantify how well our equation describes the relationship between the dependent and independent variable?

Coefficient of Determination (R2): the portion of the variance in the dependent variable that is predictable by the independent variable

Ranges from 0 to 1: R2 = 0: The value of the dependent variable cannot be predicted by the value of the independent variable (no correlation)
R2 = 1: The value of the dependent variable is perfectly predictable given a value of the independent variable
R2 = 0.9: 90% of variance in the dependent variable is predictable from the independent variable
Cautionx when interpreting R2

It’s to describe a linear relationship
Higher R2 ≠ better (or more appropriate) model
“Low” R2 doesn’t mean it’s “bad”. R2 values aren’t good or bad.
R2 can be highly influenced by outliers. LOOK AT YOUR DATA!!

Tests whether the overall regression model is statistically significant.

title: Lecture 09
text:
Diagnostics
Residuals vs Fitted Plot



plot(model, which = 1)









Purpose:
Checks for non-linearity and homoscedasticity (constant variance of residuals).
Interpretation:

Ideally, points should be randomly scattered around the horizontal line at zero.
If you see a clear pattern (e.g., a curve), this suggests that your model is missing some non-linearity.
If residuals spread out more as fitted values increase, it suggests heteroscedasticity (non-constant variance).

Lecture 09
text:
Bad Data = Bad Model
🚨 Garbage In, Garbage Out 🚨
🔴 Poor Data Quality Leads to Poor Predictions

Incomplete, inaccurate, or biased data skews model outcomes.
No amount of complex modeling can fix bad input data.

⚠️️ Common Data Issues:

Missing Values → Leads to biased or misleading insights.
Incorrect Labels → Misguides supervised learning models.
Outliers & Noise → Reduces model reliability.
Data Drift → Causes models to become outdated.

✅ Key Takeaway: Better data = Better models. Prioritize data cleaning, validation, and monitoring before training models!

title: Lecture 09
text: Visualizing Residual spread

title: Lecture 09
text:
Model Explainabilty
How well does our equation describes the relationship between the dependent and independent variable?

Coefficient of Determination (R2): the portion of the variance in the dependent variable that is predictable by the independent variable

Ranges from 0 to 1:

R2 = 0: The value of the dependent variable cannot be predicted by the value of the independent variable (no correlation)
R2 = 1: The value of the dependent variable is perfectly predictable given a value of the independent variable
R2 = 0.9: 90% of variance in the dependent variable is predictable from the independent variable

title: Lecture 09
text:
Validitiy?


Check quickly for normality and *scedasticity

shapiro.test(data$residuals)

    Shapiro-Wilk normality test

data:  data$residuals
W = 0.95801, p-value = 3.568e-08

data:  data$residuals
W = 0.95801, p-value = 3.568e-08

title: Lecture 09
text:
Multiple R-squared & Adjusted R-squared

Multiple R-squared: Proportion of variance in the dependent variable explained by the model.
Adjusted R-squared: Adjusted for the number of predictors, preventing overfitting.

Multiple R-squared:  0.7621,    Adjusted R-squared:  0.7614

title: Lecture 09
text:
F-statistic and model p-value

Tests whether the overall regression model is statistically significant.
A small p-value suggests the model is significant.
These outputs provide key insights into the model’s goodness-of-fit and statistical significance of predictors.

F-statistic:  1060 on 1 and 331 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16

title: Lecture 09
text:
Normal Q-Q Plot



plot(model, which = 2) 









Purpose:
Checks if residuals are normally distributed.
Interpretation:

If residuals follow a normal distribution, they should fall roughly along the 45-degree reference line.
Systematic deviations (e.g., S-shaped curves) indicate non-normality, which might affect inference and prediction intervals.

title: Lecture 09
text:
Scale-Location Plot



plot(model, which = 3)









Purpose:
Checks for homoscedasticity (constant variance of residuals).
Interpretation:

This plot shows the square root of the standardized residuals against the fitted values.
If the spread (vertical axis) is roughly constant across fitted values, homoscedasticity is satisfied.
A fan-like pattern (residuals increasing or decreasing with fitted values) indicates heteroscedasticity.

title: Lecture 09
text:
Cook’s Distance Plot



plot(model, which = 4) 









Purpose:
Identifies influential data points that have a large impact on the model.
Interpretation:

Cook’s distance measures how much the regression coefficients would change if a particular observation were removed.
Points with high Cook’s distance (typically above 0.5 or 1) should be examined, as they may disproportionately affect the model.
If a few points stand out, they might be outliers or high-leverage points, and you should investigate whether they are errors or legitimate influential points.

title: Lecture 09
text:
Residuals vs Leverage Plot



plot(model, which = 5) 









Purpose:
Identifies influential observations that might disproportionately affect the model.
Interpretation:

Leverage measures how extreme a point’s predictor values are.
Residuals measure how far a point’s response value is from the fitted line.
The red dashed line represents Cook’s distance; points beyond this line might be influential.
If a point has both high leverage and large residuals, it might unduly influence the regression and should be investigated.

title: Lecture 09

What is lm

class(model)
[1] "lm"
typeof(model)
[1] "list"








What is s3 class


S3 is a lightweight and flexible object-oriented system in R that allows defining custom classes by assigning a “class” attribute to lists or other base R objects. Methods for S3 classes are dispatched based on the generic function called, using a naming convention like generic.classname(), and R selects the appropriate method based on the object’s class. While S3 lacks formal encapsulation and inheritance mechanisms, it is widely used in R packages due to its simplicity and ease of extension.

Lecture 09/10
text:
This Week

Linear Models: Introduction to Models in R
Understanding the nest/map approach of modeling in R


How to use nest and map to iterate over groups
How to use broom to tidy up model outputs

title: Lecture 09/10
text:
What is Modeling?

A model is a simplified representation of reality.
They helps understand/explain, predict, and analyze complex systems.
Common in environmental science, engineering, and many other fields.

title: Lecture 09/10
text:
Types of Models

Physical Models

Scale replicas of real-world systems.
Example: A wind tunnel model of an airplane.



Conceptual Models

Diagrams or frameworks illustrating relationships.
Example: The water cycle.



Mathematical Models

Use equations to describe processes.
Example: Hydrologic models for streamflow prediction.



Statistical Models

Use data and probability to make predictions.
Example: Regression models for climate trends.

title: Lecture 09/10
text:
Why Use Models?

Models …
✅ allow testing scenarios without real-world risks.
✅ provide insights into system behavior.
✅ provide interpretability and easier communication
✅ support improving understanding and making predictions.
✅ are useful for decision-making and policy development.



Limitations of Models
🔴 Simplifications: Models are always approximations, not perfect representations if the critical driving forces aren’t captured, accuracy can be unpredictable.
🔴 Uncertainty: Data quality and assumptions affect accuracy.
🔴 Computational Cost: Some models require high processing power.

title: Lecture 09/10
text:
Bad Data = Bad Model

🚨 Garbage In, Garbage Out 🚨
🔴 Poor Data Quality Leads to Poor Predictions

Incomplete, inaccurate, or biased data skews model outcomes.
No amount of complex modeling can fix bad input data.

⚠️️ Common Data Issues:

Missing Values → Leads to biased or misleading insights.
Incorrect Labels → Misguides supervised learning models.
Outliers & Noise → Reduces model reliability.
Data Drift → Causes models to become outdated.

✅ Key Takeaway: Better data = Better models. Prioritize data cleaning, validation, and monitoring before training models!

title: Lecture 09/10
section: Visualizing Data with visdat in R
text:
Visualizing Data with visdat in R

What is visdat?

visdat is an R package for quick visualizations of data structure and missing values
Helps diagnose issues in datasets before analysis
Key Functions 🔹 vis_dat(data): Overview of data types

🔹 vis_miss(data): Visualizes missing values
🔹 vis_cor(data): Displays correlations
🔹 vis_guess(data):Shows inferred data types



Why Use visdat?
✅ Quick insights into data
✅ Identifies missing values easily
✅ Helps in preprocessing decisions

title: Lecture 09/10
text:
Examples

#install.packages("visdat") # Install the package
library(visdat)             # Load the package





vis_dat(penguins)   










vis_miss(penguins)

title: Lecture 09/10
text:
Data Cleaning

What is data cleaning?

The process of detecting, correcting, or removing corrupt, inaccurate, or incomplete data.
Ensures data quality, reliability, and usability for analysis.



Why is data cleaning important?

Duplicates and missing data can significantly impact the performance and reliability of machine learning and statistical models. Here’s how each issue affects modeling:

title: Lecture 09/10
text:
Impact of Duplicates

Bias in Model Training:
🔴 If duplicates exist in the training data, the model may overfit to repeated observations, leading to an unrealistic representation of real-world data.


Skewed Distributions:
🔴 Duplicates can artificially inflate the frequency of certain patterns, misleading statistical analyses and causing models to favor duplicated values disproportionately.


Computational Inefficiency:
🔴 Extra, redundant data increases computational load, leading to longer training times and higher memory usage without adding new information.


Overestimation of Model Performance:
🔴 If duplicates exist in both training and test sets, the model might appear to perform better than it actually does because it has seen the exact data points before.

title: Lecture 09/10
text:
Impact of Missing Data

Bias in Predictions:
🔴 If missing values are not random (e.g., more missing values in a particular category), models trained on incomplete data may develop biased decision rules.


Reduced Model Accuracy:
🔴 Missing values reduce the amount of information available to learn patterns, leading to weaker predictions and generalizations.


Issues with Certain Algorithms:
🔴 Some models, like linear regression and decision trees, can handle missing data through imputation or by ignoring missing values, but others (like most neural networks) require complete data.


Complications in Feature Engineering:
🔴 Many feature transformations, such as standardization and encoding, may not work correctly with missing values, leading to poor feature representation.

title: Lecture 09/10
text:
Handling Duplicates and Missing Data

Options for Duplicates:

Remove exact duplicates when they don’t add information.
Analyze near-duplicates to determine if they should be merged, retained, or removed.


df <- df %>% 
  distinct()



For Missing Data:

Use imputation techniques (mean, median, mode, regression-based, or KNN imputation). -Remove records if missing data is minimal and its removal won’t introduce bias.
Use models that handle missing data natively (e.g., XGBoost can handle missing values).
Properly handling duplicates and missing data improves model performance, reliability, and interpretability, ensuring that predictions are more accurate and generalizable.


## Removal
df <- df %>% 
  drop_na()

# Imputation
df <- df %>% 
  mutate(x = mean(x, na.rm = TRUE))

title: Lecture 09/10
text: Statistical Models

title: Lecture 09/10
text:
Linear Models

A Linear Model is a statistical method for modeling relationships between a dependent variable and one or more independent variables.

✅ Commonly used in regression analysis.
✅ Simple and interpretable.
✅ Useful for prediction and understanding relationships in data.
✅ Forms the foundation for more complex models.

title: Lecture 09/10
text:
Introduction to Linear Models

Linear models help us understand relationships between variables.
Describe relationships between variables using a mathematical equation that assumes a linear relationship of “best fit”.
They take the form: \[ y = \beta_0 + \beta_1 x + \epsilon \]
Where:

( y ) is the response variable.
( x ) is the predictor variable.
\(\beta_0\) is the intercept (value of ( y ) when ( x = 0 )).
\(\beta_1\) is the slope (change in ( y ) for a unit change in ( x )).
\(\epsilon\) is the error term.

title: Lecture 09/10
section: How do we fine the “Line of Best Fit”?
text:
How do we fine the “Line of Best Fit”?

Method of Ordinary Least Squares (OLS)
Ordinary Least Squares finds the line of best fit for a linear model (in the form of y = mx + b) by minimizing the sum of the residuals squared

where:

residuals are the distance between the sample value (for the dependent variable) and the value predicted by the equation for each value of the independent variable.

title: Lecture 09/10
section: Four Main Assumptions for linear regression
text:
Four Main Assumptions for linear regression

Linearity of the relationship between dependent and independent variables


Dot

. . .

Independence of the errors (no serial correlation): Error in one measurement (observation) should not influence errors for any other observations

. . .

Homoscedasticty (constant variance) of the errors

versus time
versus the predicted values


. . .

Normality of the residuals

title: Lecture 09/10
text: Visualizing Residual spread

title: Lecture 09/10
text:
Model Explainabilty

How well does our equation describes the relationship between the dependent and independent variable?

Coefficient of Determination (R2): the portion of the variance in the dependent variable that is predictable by the independent variable



Ranges from 0 to 1:

R2 = 0: The value of the dependent variable cannot be predicted by the value of the independent variable (no correlation)
R2 = 1: The value of the dependent variable is perfectly predictable given a value of the independent variable
R2 = 0.9: 90% of variance in the dependent variable is predictable from the independent variable

title: Lecture 09/10
text:
Model Explainabilty






Warning



🚨 Caution when interpreting R2 🚨 - It’s to describe a linear relationship - Higher R2 ≠ better (or more appropriate) model - “Low” R2 doesn’t mean it’s “bad”. R2 values aren’t good or bad. - R2 can be highly influenced by outliers. LOOK AT YOUR DATA!!

title: Lecture 09/10
text:
The lm() Function in R
Basic Syntax:

model <- lm(y ~ x, data = dataset)

Where:

y: Dependent variable (response).
~: Describes a formula as LHS ~ RHS (remember facet_*)
x: Independent variable (predictor).
dataset: data.frame/tibble containing variables.

data   <-  penguins |> 
  drop_na()

What is s3 class



S3 is a lightweight and flexible object-oriented system in R that allows defining custom classes by assigning a “class” attribute to lists or other base R objects. Methods for S3 classes are dispatched based on the generic function called, using a naming convention like generic.classname(), and R selects the appropriate method based on the object’s class. While S3 lacks formal encapsulation and inheritance mechanisms, it is widely used in R packages due to its simplicity and ease of extension.

title: Lecture 09/10

Coefficients
Provides estimates of the regression coefficients, their standard errors, t-values, and p-values.
             Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
(Intercept) 1.370e+02  1.999e+00   68.56   <2e-16 ***
body_mass_g 1.520e-02  4.667e-04   32.56   <2e-16 ***
---
Signif. codes:  0 ‘***’ 0.001 ‘**’ 0.01 ‘*’ 0.05 ‘.’ 0.1 ‘ ’ 1
✅ Estimate: The estimated coefficient for each predictor.
✅ Std. Error: The standard error of each coefficient.
✅ t value: The test statistic for testing if the coefficient is significantly different from zero.
✅ Pr(>|t|): The p-value for each coefficient.
✅ Significance codes: highly significant, marginally significant, not significant).

✅ Residual standard error: Measures the average deviation of residuals from the regression line.
✅ Multiple R-squared: Proportion of variance in the dependent variable explained by the model.
✅ Adjusted R-squared: Adjusted for the number of predictors, preventing overfitting.
✅ F-statistic: Tests whether the overall regression model is statistically significant.
✅ A small p-value suggests the model is significant.

title: Lecture 09/10
text:
Diagnostics

Residuals vs Fitted Plot



plot(model, which = 1)










Purpose:
Checks for non-linearity and homoscedasticity (constant variance of residuals).


Interpretation:

Ideally, points should be randomly scattered around the horizontal line at zero.
If you see a clear pattern (e.g., a curve), this suggests that your model is missing some non-linearity.
If residuals spread out more as fitted values increase, it suggests heteroscedasticity (non-constant variance).

title: Lecture 09/10
text:
Normal Q-Q Plot



plot(model, which = 2) 










Purpose:
Checks if residuals are normally distributed.


Interpretation:

If residuals follow a normal distribution, they should fall roughly along the 45-degree reference line.
Systematic deviations (e.g., S-shaped curves) indicate non-normality, which might affect inference and prediction intervals.

title: Lecture 09/10
text:
Scale-Location Plot



plot(model, which = 3)










Purpose:
Checks for homoscedasticity (constant variance of residuals).


Interpretation:

This plot shows the square root of the standardized residuals against the fitted values.
If the spread (vertical axis) is roughly constant across fitted values, homoscedasticity is satisfied.
A fan-like pattern (residuals increasing or decreasing with fitted values) indicates heteroscedasticity.

title: Lecture 09/10
text:
Cook’s Distance Plot



plot(model, which = 4) 










Purpose:
Identifies influential data points that have a large impact on the model.


Interpretation:

Cook’s distance measures how much the regression coefficients would change if a particular observation were removed.
Points with high Cook’s distance (typically above 0.5 or 1) should be examined, as they may disproportionately affect the model.
If a few points stand out, they might be outliers or high-leverage points, and you should investigate whether they are errors or legitimate influential points.

title: Lecture 09/10
text:
Residuals vs Leverage Plot



plot(model, which = 5) 










Purpose:
Identifies influential observations that might disproportionately affect the model.


Interpretation:

Leverage measures how extreme a point’s predictor values are.
Residuals measure how far a point’s response value is from the fitted line.
The red dashed line represents Cook’s distance; points beyond this line might be influential.
If a point has both high leverage and large residuals, it might unduly influence the regression and should be investigated.

What is broom?

The broom package helps tidy up model outputs for further analysis or reporting.

title: Lecture 09/10
section: Linear Models as the Basis for Machine Learning
text:
Linear Models as the Basis for Machine Learning

Why is lm() Fundamental to ML?
Linear regression is the simplest form of a predictive model and forms the basis of many ML algorithms, such as:


1. Logistic Regression (for classification)

Example: Predicting water contamination based on pH, turbidity, and dissolved oxygen. 



2. Support Vector Machines (Linear Kernel)

Example: Classifying land cover types (urban vs. vegetation) using remote sensing data. 



3. Neural Networks (Linear Combinations in Layers)

Example: Modeling soil moisture dynamics with meteorological variables.

title: Lecture 09/10
section: OLS-Based ML Methods in Environmental Science
text:
OLS-Based ML Methods in Environmental Science

4. Generalized Linear Models (GLMs)

Example: Predicting species distribution based on climate variables (temperature, precipitation). 



5. Regularization: Ridge & Lasso Regression

Example: Predicting air pollution levels (PM2.5) while selecting the most important features. 



6. Partial Least Squares Regression (PLSR)

Useful for high-dimensional data (e.g., hyperspectral satellite imagery).
Example: Predicting chlorophyll-a concentration in lakes.

title: Lecture 09/10
section: OLS-Based ML Methods in Environmental Science
text:
OLS-Based ML Methods in Environmental Science

7. Principal Component Regression (PCR)

Reduces collinearity using PCA before regression.
Example: Identifying key meteorological drivers of air quality changes. 



8. Generalized Additive Models (GAMs)

Allows nonlinear relationships using splines.
Example: Modeling temperature impacts on species migration. 



9. Mixed-Effects Models (LMMs/GLMMs)

Handles spatial and hierarchical dependencies.
Example: Estimating streamflow changes across watersheds.

title: Lecture 09/10
section: OLS-Based ML Methods in Environmental Science
text:
OLS-Based ML Methods in Environmental Science

10. Elastic Net Regression

Combines Ridge & Lasso for variable selection and shrinkage.
Example: Modeling urban heat island effects. 



11. Bayesian Regression

Incorporates prior knowledge and uncertainty.
Example: Predicting future drought probabilities based on historical trends. 



12. Deep Learning & Matrix Multiplication

Many deep learning models extend OLS concepts through matrix operations.
Example: Using CNNs for forest fire detection in satellite imagery.

While atomic vectors must store base R data types (Logical, character, numeric)










lists can store whatever they want!

title: Lecture 10
text:
Internal groupings

nest() and map() are functions from the tidyverse, primarily used with the tidyr and purrr packages.
They allow for efficient list-column workflows and functional programming in R.
Useful for grouped operations, iterative calculations, and data wrangling.

title: Lecture 10
text:
What is nest()?

nest() converts a grouped dataset into a list-column format.
It allows you to keep related observations together in nested data.frames.


nested_data <- penguins |> 
  nest(data = -species)

title: Lecture 10
text:
Working over list-columns
Verbs like mutate work well across columns, but cannot work over nested lists (e.g. a list-column of a data.frame (list!))

For this, we need additional tooling.


"purrr" %in% tidyverse_packages()
[1] TRUE

title: Lecture 10
text:
Introduction to purrr
purrr is an R package designed to enhance iteration, functional programming, and list manipulation. It provides a cohesive and readable alternative to base R functions like lapply(), sapply(), and apply(). The core philosophy of purrr is to make function application more predictable and consistent.

title: Lecture 10
text:
Why purrr?

Simplifies iteration over lists, vectors, and data frames.
Ensures consistent output types.
Encourages functional programming paradigms.
Works seamlessly with tidyverse.

title: Lecture 10
text:
1. map()

The map() function applies a function to each element of a list or vector and returns a list.

title: Lecture 10
text:
2. map_*() Variants

map() → Returns a list
map_lgl() → Returns a logical vector
map_int() → Returns an integer vector
map_dbl() → Returns a double (numeric) vector
map_chr() → Returns a character vector


Example:

numbers <- list(1, 2, 3, 4, 5)
squared_numbers <- map_dbl(numbers, ~ .x^2)
print(squared_numbers) # Numeric vector of squared numbers
[1]  1  4  9 16 25

title: Lecture 10
text:
3. map2()
map2() applies a function to two lists element-wise.

Example:

list1 <- list(1, 2, 3)
list2 <- list(4, 5, 6)
sums <- map2(list1, list2, ~ .x + .y)
print(sums) # List of sums
[[1]]
[1] 5

[[2]]
[1] 7

[[3]]
[1] 9

title: Lecture 10
text:
4. pmap()
pmap() extends map2() to handle multiple lists.

Example:

a <- list(1, 2, 3)
b <- list(4, 5, 6)
c <- list(7, 8, 9)
results <- pmap(list(a = a, b = b, c = c), function(a,b,c) a + b + c)
print(results) # List of sums of three elements
[[1]]
[1] 12

[[2]]
[1] 15

[[3]]
[1] 18

title: Lecture 10
text:
5. map_dfr() and map_dfc()
These functions return data frames instead of lists:

df_list <- list(
  data.frame(x = 1:3, y = 4:6),
  data.frame(x = 7:9, y = 10:12)
)
combined_df <- map_dfr(df_list, identity)
print(combined_df) # Row-bind data frames
  x  y
1 1  4
2 2  5
3 3  6
4 7 10
5 8 11
6 9 12

title: Lecture 10
text:
Error Handling with safely()
safely()

Wraps a function and returns a list with results and errors.


map(list(1, 10, -5), log)
[[1]]
[1] 0

[[2]]
[1] 2.302585

[[3]]
[1] NaN
map(list(1, 10, -5), safely(log))
[[1]]
[[1]]$result
[1] 0

[[1]]$error
NULL


[[2]]
[[2]]$result
[1] 2.302585

[[2]]$error
NULL


[[3]]
[[3]]$result
[1] NaN

[[3]]$error
NULL

title: Lecture 10
text: Error Handling with possibly()

title: Lecture 10
text:
possibly()

Returns a default value in case of an error.


safe_log <- possibly(log, otherwise = NA)
result <- map_dbl(list(1, 10, -5), safe_log)
print(result) # NA for the negative input
[1] 0.000000 2.302585      NaN

title: Lecture 10
text:
What is purrr::map()?

map() applies a function over a list or vector.
It works similarly to lapply() but with better integration into tidyverse workflows.


library(purrr)
numbers <- list(1, 2, 3, 4, 5)
squared <- map(numbers, ~ .x^2)
print(squared) # List of squared numbers
[[1]]
[1] 1

[[2]]
[1] 4

[[3]]
[1] 9

[[4]]
[1] 16

[[5]]
[1] 25


Explanation:

The .x notation inside map() refers to the data frame being operated on.

title: Lecture 10

So what?

So you might be asking why all this extra work over group_by/summarize?
The reason is the flexability that lists offer over vector in what they can store!

  group_by(species) %>% 
  mutate(lm = lm(flipper_length_mm ~ body_mass_g, data = .))

title: Lecture 10
text:
Combining nest() and map()

nest() structures the data into list-column objects
map() applies functions over list objects to each nested dataset.
model objects are S3 list objects with methods that can be applied
Can be used for modeling, summaries, and transformations.


Example: Linear Regression by Group

(nested_data <- penguins |> 
   drop_na() |> 
   nest(data = -species))

Explanation:

The tidy() function extracts the coefficients from the linear models stored in the model column and formats them into a tidy data frame.
This makes it easier to summarize or report on the results.

title: Lecture 10
text:
Final

x = nested_data|> 
  mutate(model =  map(data, ~lm(flipper_length_mm ~ body_mass_g, data = .x))) |> 
  mutate(lm = map(model, broom::tidy),
         summary   = map(model, summary),
         r2 = map_dbl(summary, "r.squared")) |> 
  unnest(lm) |> 
  select(-data, -model)

y = select(x, species, term, estimate) 

pivot_wider(y, names_from = species, values_from = estimate) |> 
  janitor::clean_names()
# A tibble: 2 × 4
  term           adelie    gentoo chinstrap
  <chr>           <dbl>     <dbl>     <dbl>
1 (Intercept) 166.      170.       151.    
2 body_mass_g   0.00661   0.00934    0.0119

z = pivot_wider(y, names_from = term, values_from = estimate) |> 
  janitor::clean_names()

ggplot(data = z, aes(x = species, y = intercept, fill = species)) +
  geom_col() +
  ggthemes::theme_clean() + 
  theme(legend.position = "bottom") + 
  labs(title = "Life Expectancy vs GDP per Capita by Continent",
       x = "Continent",
       y = "Linear Model Intercept")








ggplot(data = y, aes(x = species, y = estimate, fill = species)) +
  geom_col() +
  facet_wrap(~term, scales = "free_y") + 
  scale_fill_manual(values = as.vector(pals::alphabet2(5))) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = as.vector(pals::ocean.haline(5))) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = pals::brewer.dark2(5)) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = pals::tol.rainbow(5)) +
  ggthemes::theme_clean() + 
  theme(legend.position = "bottom") + 
  labs(title = "Life Expectancy vs GDP per Capita by Continent",
       x = "Continent",
       y = "Linear Model Intercept")

title: Lecture 10
text:
Conclusion
nest() is useful for grouping and restructuring data. map() enables functional programming and efficient iteration. broom() provides a way to tidy up model outputs for easier interpretation and reporting.
Together, they provide a powerful framework for handling grouped analyses in R.

title: Lecture 09
text:
Remember … Vectors?

Vectors come in two types: atomic and lists
For atomic vectors, all elements must have the same type;
For lists, elements can have different types.
NULL serves as a generic zero length vector.




df = data.frame (x = 1:10, y = letters[1:10])
df$list_element = vector("list", length = nrow(df))

2 2 b         NULL
3 3 c         NULL
4 4 d         NULL
5 5 e         NULL
6 6 f         NULL

title: Lecture 09/10

Lists

Atomic vectors store base types (logical, character, numeric).
Lists can store anything (including other lists!).

  lm(flipper_length_mm ~ body_mass_g, data = data),
  lm(flipper_length_mm ~ bill_length_mm, data = data),
  lm(flipper_length_mm ~ bill_depth_mm, data = data)
)

title: Lecture 09
text:
Internal groupings

nest() and map() are functions from the tidyverse, primarily used with the tidyr and purrr packages.
They allow for efficient list-column workflows and functional programming in R.
Useful for grouped operations, iterative calculations, and data wrangling.

title: Lecture 09/10
text:
What is nest()?
nest converts groups of data into list-columns (nested tibbles).

title: Lecture 09
text:
Working over list-columns
Verbs like mutate work well across columns, but cannot work over nested lists (e.g. a list-column of a data.frame (list!))

For this, we need additional tooling.


"purrr" %in% tidyverse_packages()
[1] TRUE

title: Lecture 09/10
text:
Introduction to purrr
✅ Verbs like mutate work well across columns, but cannot work over nested lists (e.g. a list-column of a tibble (list!))
✅ purrr is an R package designed to enhance iteration, functional programming, and list manipulation. It provides a cohesive and readable alternative to base R functions like lapply(), sapply(), and apply(). The core philosophy of purrr is to make function application more predictable and consistent.
✅ Much like dplyr /groups work together, purrr/nests operate harmoniously

"purrr" %in% tidyverse_packages()
[1] TRUE

title: Lecture 09/10
text:
Why purrr?
✅ Simplifies iteration over lists, vectors, and data frames.
✅ Ensures consistent output types.
✅ Encourages functional programming paradigms.
✅ Works seamlessly with tidyverse.

title: Lecture 09/10
text:
1. map()

The map() function applies a function to each element of a list or vector and returns a list.
It works similarly to lapply() but with better integration into tidyverse workflows.


numbers <- list(1, 2, 3, 4, 5)
map(numbers, ~ .x^2)
[[1]]
[1] 1

[[2]]
[1] 4

[[3]]
[1] 9

[[4]]
[1] 16

[[5]]
[1] 25


Explanation:

The .x notation inside map() refers to the data frame being operated on.

title: Lecture 09
text:
What is purrr::map()?

map() applies a function over a list or vector.
It works similarly to lapply() but with better integration into tidyverse workflows.


library(purrr)
numbers <- list(1, 2, 3, 4, 5)
squared <- map(numbers, ~ .x^2)
print(squared) # List of squared numbers
[[1]]
[1] 1

[[2]]
[1] 4

[[3]]
[1] 9

[[4]]
[1] 16

[[5]]
[1] 25

Explanation:

The .x notation inside map() refers to the data frame being operated on.

title: Lecture 09/10
text:
2. map_*() Variants

map() → Returns a list
map_lgl() → Returns a logical vector
map_int() → Returns an integer vector
map_dbl() → Returns a double (numeric) vector
map_chr() → Returns a character vector


Example:

numbers <- list(1, 2, 3, 4, 5)
map_dbl(numbers, ~ .x^2)
[1]  1  4  9 16 25

title: Lecture 09/10
text:
3. map2()
map2() applies a function to two lists element-wise.

Example:

list1 <- list(1, 2, 3)
list2 <- list(4, 5, 6)
map2(list1, list2, ~ .x + .y)
[[1]]
[1] 5

[[2]]
[1] 7

[[3]]
[1] 9

title: Lecture 09/10
text:
4. pmap()
pmap() extends map2() to handle multiple lists.

Example:

a <- list(1, 2, 3)
b <- list(4, 5, 6)
c <- list(7, 8, 9)
pmap(list(a = a, b = b, c = c), function(a,b,c) a + b + c)
[[1]]
[1] 12

[[2]]
[1] 15

[[3]]
[1] 18

title: Lecture 09/10
Lecture 09/10
text:
So what?

So you might be asking why all this extra work over group_by/summarize?
The reason is the flexibility that lists offer over vector in what they can store!


penguins |> 
  drop_na() |> 
  group_by(species) %>% 
  mutate(lm = lm(flipper_length_mm ~ body_mass_g, data = .))

ℹ In group 1: `species = Adelie`.
Caused by error:
! `lm` must be a vector, not a <lm> object.

title: Lecture 09/10
text:
Combining nest() and map()

nest() structures the data into list-column objects
map() applies functions over list objects to each nested dataset.
model objects are S3 list objects with methods that can be applied
Can be used for modeling, summaries, and transformations.
